The basis that gave rise to the birth of IBM comes from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "fix clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the business man Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory advice.
Flint set the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm basis for corporate culture and identity).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business equipment, from meat cutters and cheese to register boxes.
