We all love and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world we always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of the grunt?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of big bands.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement arises from a group of friends and it's a little unusual.
Every now and then, there's a band in a city, but it's a lot more strange when five or ten bands come out at the same time as one city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on her tour, so we are lucky to be friends with them all yet and honor us being part of that Seattle sound that emerged.
It is also very strange that a band like yours will remain united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands last.
First of all, I think we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we all care about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened that give everyone freedom to experience.
We trust each other with each other's music and couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word of fame has not been simple; yet, thanks to your success, they have been able to do whatever they want.
How do you find a balance sheet?
As we have grown up, it has been easier to find a balance sheet.
We make sure you don't be too busy because it's easy to fall into that game of the great crowds and the people who love your music.
While one remembers that people are there for music, that reminds you that you must respect music and what brought it, without getting encapsulated for being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was something great.
We went on a band for almost three years and never posted a record until after Andy died (Andrew Woods).
There were many frustrations because it would last so long and most importantly we are still very friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture of the incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was a surprising human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
