As a bassist, what are their influences?
They're so many.
Among the first ones that happen to me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
They're so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunt relevant despite being no longer a fashion?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, I remember the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that came up at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's something wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the result of this change?
It's interesting because I think there's a couple of songs in the new album that might look lighter, but there's also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs though they might sound a little positive.
With both of them, when Ed touched me, I cried when I listened to them and they were deeply dark songs.
I think that when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a relative or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
