MSS announces protocol to find gene obesity
Leads Social Security an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents' protocol, which will enable them to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Specialties Hospital of the National Medical Centre Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Advanced Research and Studies Centre (Cinvesav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate in the population whether or not they are entitled to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Ponent Mexico State) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the objective of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day, he stated that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, to implement specific food questionnaires.
You will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger such diseases as diabetes or renal failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants are applied anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, and insulin and genetics (the aim is to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this research is based on the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 percent in obesity, and in the case of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed,' highlighted the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others in their genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess of energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in fat form.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the integral evaluation of children, which allows them to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) on the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability of metabolic and even prediabetes alterations.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are told each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle that they must make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic sufferings: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugared beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, et cetera) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would prevent berries
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 basins each rain season in the Mexican Valley Metropolitan Zone, warned Rafael Herrera Najera, researcher at the UNAM's Faculty of Chemicals (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the berries, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemicals, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north, to improve its performance and hence the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give to the floor their characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrades has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, warned the expert in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve the asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were to be modified asphalt, the chemical engineer felt it would be even better.
