So was the work of the caleño that identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went to history like the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th, a lophoscopist of Cali's ITC went to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", through his fingerprinting.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the ITC section, that week played the "availability" shift to Eliasar González, a man from Port Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the start of his career, González worked in municipalities of the Chocó, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms of the hands and feet.
The operating week against Alfonso Cano alias Elizar warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
Friday night he left for the Caucasus on a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so they asked him to carry the decactillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was naked, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Elias compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye failed him: he was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man coming from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was the chief of the Farcs.
Searching for the trace
For a dictator of the Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliasar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactioscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can become a key to the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of bodies, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the people captured.
When captured, many delinquents present false ballots or have no papers.
We take the fingerprint print and look it up in the database.
The investigator reported that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to take out a fingerprint, but in that case we could get the trace of all the hand and identify the criminal, who had participated in different thefts," she recalled.
Traces may also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, in fact, a trace in the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
An ITC dictiloscopicist explained that in the objects "the traces are taken out with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Register.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said ITC expert.
He made it clear that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that touches becomes trace.
However, if it can be used, if the respective quota is made.
