Energy policy:
the facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate for an election meeting to be a time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the options proposed.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, there will have to be a growing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
This is not the case with Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or with Switzerland, which only aims to build last-generation power stations.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, by citing some examples, continue to be determined by their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resumed the construction of a power station interrupted after the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality runs counter to such discourse.
The choice of Berlin will mean a rise in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, harmful effects will be noted.
It must be taken into account in the case of Denmark.
Europe's champion in the wind sector, of which 30% of its electricity is obtained, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to wind interference; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would entail a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would remain realistic to the wonderful declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not show opposition by principle to this type of energy, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 head jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs that specialize in international markets and can create non-movable jobs.
If France decided to give up nuclear power, it would entail the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros per year in French nuclear equipment and services exports.
What electrician would charge an EPR designed to run sixty years, when your manufacturer's collapse is expected?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miracle source of electricity production, as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Security Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamenville.
Our highly professional teams are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences either to people or to the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural catastrophes, resulting in the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as the previous two did.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting these phenomena.
