However, economic analysis is rarely considered.
The point is that, on this subject, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900.000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million migrant workers", while on the left, the tone set it Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the problem of migration.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Definition Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limitation of immigration undermines growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, with pressure to reduce their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the wages and employment of the nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows represents a rise in the long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches 30 years of age will make a net contribution (increased costs) of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that were missing "with his teeth."
These teeth, which discouraged immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it is only necessary to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious but also fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, during the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the crowns in Greece.
Some may have thought that, in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and as directly as possible.
We know, from Napoleon, "the Little One," that was about something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough alone and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum in this regard had a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return from the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruousness.
It must be reflected on this ambivalence to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now been displaced and that in many cases Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a high in the vacuum of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take action, but a common exercise, of full right, quiet and continuous, from choices and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to finish the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that bends the orders of markets and rating agencies, which suffer their impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that suffers from humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty regains the momentum of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investments.
The exit of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without a total democratic legitimacy, except in order to lead us to disaster.
After having fought this Socialist and Jacques Delors proposal for a long time, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
