The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Filon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km to communicate the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are talking about the possibility of building a third tube by the same route.
For Gazprom, the finalization in time of this enormous work presents areas of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land flow by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it by closing its access to the markets in Western Europe.
At the highlight of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to make its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organicly," said François Fillon during the gas pipeline opening, demonstrating to what extent the major gas sector contracts are as political as economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchorages.
It is located at the bottom of the sea, about 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman of North Stream society.
The protection measures for fauna and flora were also extremely necessary.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A monitoring platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project's leaders resigned from it when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently in the sea off its coasts.
"In case you find out, we'll interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, gas pipeline gas will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders find it unlikely that a flight will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to the forecasts, will be run every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a underwater robot, carried out by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the form of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full travel days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without need of any repair.
Gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which has 51% of the stakes.
She was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been brought to an end by 30% with the contributions of shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not get over their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenditure.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Some valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
The total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
