Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of the disabled are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Disabling?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress that has been achieved for fifteen years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average.
"But there's still a lot to do."
It is worth mentioning that disabled people continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37 per cent is over 50 (an average 17 per cent).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the question of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of people progresses, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people on wheelchairs, physical or intellectual".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available in 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"Now we reach around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishment "subject to this contribution" as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased from 2007 to 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees on their staff, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
